42:59.500 --> 43:04.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The entrepreneurs
themselves, one of the
things we need to point
out is that venture capital

43:06.866 --> 43:09.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as currently constructed
is leaving billions of
dollars on the table
because they're overlooking

43:12.500 --> 43:17.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
underrepresented entrepreneurs
who have great ideas and who
can serve real communities'

43:19.466 --> 43:20.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
real needs.

43:20.466 --> 43:21.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SREENIVASAN: All right.

43:21.966 --> 43:23.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Freada Kapor Klein joining
us from Oakland tonight.

43:23.300 --> 43:25.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thanks so much.

43:25.533 --> 43:30.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KLEIN: Thank you.

43:31.566 --> 43:35.566 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(END VIDEOTAPE)

43:35.566 --> 43:40.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Chuck Berry was a
pioneer in his field, often
referred to as the father of

43:42.000 --> 43:45.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
rock 'n' roll who influenced
a generation of musicians.

43:45.733 --> 43:50.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Now, three months after
his death at age 90,
he's back, in a way.

43:51.466 --> 43:52.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown explains.

43:52.533 --> 43:54.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

43:54.733 --> 43:59.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN, PBS NEWSHOUR
CORRESPONDENT: You know
it when you hear it.

44:02.000 --> 44:07.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Beginning in the mid-1950s,
Chuck Berry helped define the
sound and look, the attitude and

44:10.400 --> 44:13.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
raw power of rock 'n' roll.

44:13.933 --> 44:18.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The man is now gone, but his
music lives on, in a new album,
titled "Chuck," berry's first

44:21.266 --> 44:23.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
album since 1979.

44:23.300 --> 44:28.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He'd worked on the project off
and on for several decades,
and on his 90th birthday,

44:29.666 --> 44:32.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
five months before his
death, had announced
its imminent release.

44:32.466 --> 44:35.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: So,
here's one of his Cadillacs.

44:35.433 --> 44:37.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: Yes.

44:37.466 --> 44:41.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN: I was joined recently
by the star's son Charles and
grandson Charlie at the National

44:43.333 --> 44:46.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Museum of African-American
History and Culture for some
personal memories of the man and

44:46.566 --> 44:48.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his music.

44:48.533 --> 44:51.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLES BERRY, JR., SON OF
CHUCK BERRY: This was a guy
when he was a little boy he sold

44:51.333 --> 44:54.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
vegetables off a
cart with his father.

44:54.400 --> 44:59.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a man that worked
at a General Motors
plant, not assembling the
cars, but as a janitor.

45:01.566 --> 45:06.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He heard from other people the
significance that he brought
to the table, but my -- he

45:08.466 --> 45:10.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
didn't really dwell on that.

45:10.533 --> 45:11.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLES BERRY III, GRANDSON
OF CHUCK BERRY: I remember in
elementary school, I'd have

45:11.966 --> 45:13.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
teachers coming up to me
like, who's your grandfather?

45:13.933 --> 45:16.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'd be like, pawpaw (ph).

45:16.766 --> 45:18.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They were like, that's so cool.

45:18.766 --> 45:22.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN (on camera): Did
you have any idea who your
grandfather was in history?

45:22.833 --> 45:27.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLES BERRY III: I always
knew he played the guitar,
but I didn't think he was like

45:27.466 --> 45:31.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this bigger than life
person to everybody else
because he was just pawpaw.

45:31.566 --> 45:32.766 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
BROWN: Yes.

45:32.766 --> 45:34.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Oh, boy, did he play
the guitar, huh?

45:34.300 --> 45:36.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHARLES BERRY III: Oh, yes.

45:36.500 --> 45:41.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN (voice-over): In fact,
both Charles and Charlie play
the guitar and had the chance

45:43.200 --> 45:45.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to play with Chuck.

45:45.033 --> 45:47.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Charles is part of the
band for many years.

45:47.800 --> 45:52.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Since Chuck's death, they've
played on, here just recently
promoting the new album on "The

45:53.400 --> 45:55.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Tonight Show".

45:55.400 --> 45:59.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The album charts Chuck
Berry's life in stages,
an autobiographical
epitaph of sorts.

46:02.000 --> 46:06.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the song "Big Boys," he
returns to his childhood with
the ambitions of a teenager,

46:06.566 --> 46:11.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
while "The Eyes of Man"
describes the wisdom
of women in his life.

46:14.033 --> 46:19.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLES BERRY JR.: It's almost
to the point that he was being
philosophical over his life

46:21.466 --> 46:26.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and letting everybody
else knows, like, hey,
from a wonderful woman
to a big boy to an

46:27.666 --> 46:31.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
eye of a man, here's my book.

46:31.966 --> 46:36.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here's the next chapter of
my life that you get to have,
and I hope you enjoy it.

46:38.933 --> 46:41.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN: Berry continued to
perform into his late '80s,
including his renowned monthly

46:41.566 --> 46:46.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
gig at Blueberry Hill,
a diner and music venue
in his native St. Louis.

46:46.133 --> 46:51.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIC CLAPTON, MUSICIAN: He's
really laid the law down for
playing that kind of music.

46:53.100 --> 46:56.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRUCE SPRINGSTEEN, MUSICIAN:
When I'm 65 or 70, I've
got to tell my grandkids.

46:56.933 --> 46:58.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Yes, I met Chuck Berry.

46:58.400 --> 47:03.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
As a matter of fact, I backed
up Chuck Berry one night.

47:03.000 --> 47:04.000 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
You did?

47:04.000 --> 47:05.966 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

47:05.966 --> 47:09.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LITTLE RICHARD, MUSICIAN:
My favorite song with
Chuck is all of 'em.

47:09.300 --> 47:14.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: His influence is
everywhere in rock music.

47:16.300 --> 47:20.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The initial cultural jolt was
jokingly portrayed in the 1985
hit movie, "Back to the Future."

47:28.500 --> 47:32.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And honored nine years
later in" Pulp Fiction."

47:32.000 --> 47:37.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEVIN STRAIT, MUSEUM CURATOR:
Rock and roll has such a firm
place in our cultural memory.

47:40.066 --> 47:43.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
BROWN: Kevin Strait is
a musical historian and
curator at the museum.

47:43.866 --> 47:46.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
STRAIT: He's one of the
primary sonic architects
of rock and roll.

47:46.933 --> 47:51.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, he helped establish this
art form that we all know and
love, and that really sort

47:51.666 --> 47:53.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of took over the world.

47:53.233 --> 47:57.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Its helm really was this
young musician from St. Louis.

47:57.000 --> 48:02.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, you know, he really sort
of helped to sort of establish
the template for how rock

48:03.733 --> 48:05.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and roll should sound.

48:05.600 --> 48:08.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, he's a
phenomenal guitar player,
phenomenal showman.

48:08.233 --> 48:13.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN: Strait acquired objects
from Berry for the museum's
musical crossroads collection,

48:14.100 --> 48:15.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
including this prized guitar.

48:15.333 --> 48:17.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
STRAIT: This guitar
is pretty special.

48:17.433 --> 48:19.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's a Gibson ES-350T.

48:19.500 --> 48:24.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, it's one of his early
touring and recording guitars
that he used, and it's nicknamed

48:24.966 --> 48:26.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Maybellene after his first hit.

48:26.233 --> 48:27.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
BROWN (on camera):
Yes, quite a first hit.

48:27.900 --> 48:31.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Quite a name, right?

48:31.600 --> 48:33.133 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(MUSIC)

48:33.133 --> 48:38.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN (voice-over): And that
red 1973 Cadillac Eldorado?

48:49.000 --> 48:54.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Berry drove it on stage in
1986 for his 60th birthday and
the filming of the documentary

48:54.866 --> 48:57.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
"Hail, Hail Rock 'n' Roll".

48:57.066 --> 49:01.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That was at the Fox Theater
in St. Louis, which had denied
him entry as a child because

49:01.833 --> 49:03.966 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
he was black.

49:03.966 --> 49:08.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CHUCK BERRY, MUSICIAN:
And my forefathers a few
blocks away were sold
on the civil courthouse

49:12.300 --> 49:17.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
steps, sold, and
that's a big change.

49:19.733 --> 49:24.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLES BERRY JR.: It was
difficult, absolutely,
but as opposed to,
man, these white people

49:25.366 --> 49:26.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are just, they're playing me.

49:26.366 --> 49:28.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
My God, I can't -- nope.

49:28.366 --> 49:33.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My dad took it as, oh, so you're
telling me I can't go in the
front of this venue to play

49:34.433 --> 49:36.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in front of this crowd.

49:36.700 --> 49:41.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
OK, I'm going to keep
writing my music.

49:42.433 --> 49:43.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They're going to change.

49:43.433 --> 49:45.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm going to make it.

49:45.633 --> 49:50.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm going to make a scenario
where the people that are
listening to my music are having

49:52.566 --> 49:56.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
such a blast that skin
color becomes irrelevant.

49:56.500 --> 50:01.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN (on camera): How do you
see what your grandfather,
what he went through and what

50:02.100 --> 50:04.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
he achieved?

50:04.100 --> 50:06.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLES BERRY III: That you
could go from selling out a
packed house to then being told

50:06.966 --> 50:08.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
you can't stay in
this hotel room.

50:08.933 --> 50:12.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is like I that probably
would have left me pretty
bitter throughout the rest of my

50:12.666 --> 50:14.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
life.

50:14.700 --> 50:19.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I don't know because what
he's done with his music and
everything, it's just that much

50:21.333 --> 50:26.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more amazing because he was
able to do it during that time.

50:27.900 --> 50:31.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
BROWN: A pioneering life
that had dramatic ups
and downs, for sure.

50:34.233 --> 50:39.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, "Chuck" the album
adds new music to what was
already an enormous legacy.

50:40.733 --> 50:44.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour", I'm
Jeffrey Brown in Washington.

50:45.433 --> 50:50.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(END VIDEOTAPE)

50:51.333 --> 50:55.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WOODRUFF: Love his music.

50:55.266 --> 50:58.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And now to another in our
"Brief but Spectacular Series".

50:58.466 --> 51:01.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Tonight, we hear
from Georgina Kleege.

51:01.000 --> 51:05.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's a lecturer in the English
department at the University
of California, Berkeley.

51:05.200 --> 51:10.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Her forthcoming book is "More
Than Meets the Eye: What
Blindness Brings to Art."

51:10.033 --> 51:12.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

51:12.633 --> 51:14.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GEORGINA KLEEGE, LECTURER,
UC BERKELEY DEPARTMENT
OF ENGLISH: It's a common
experience for people

51:14.733 --> 51:17.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with disabilities to feel that
they are being stared at or to
notice they are being stared

51:18.266 --> 51:20.266 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
at.

51:20.266 --> 51:24.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in fact, blind people
can feel that, too, a kind of
collective intake of breath even

51:26.900 --> 51:31.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
if nobody says anything, you can
tell when you attract attention.

51:37.900 --> 51:42.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I am legally blind, I
became legally blind, I was
diagnosed when I was 11.

51:44.466 --> 51:48.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I probably lost my vision
gradually over a few years.

51:48.033 --> 51:53.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I remember feeling that I
wasn't supposed to feel anything
about it, because there wasn't

51:53.933 --> 51:55.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
anything anybody could do.

51:55.800 --> 51:59.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My complicated relationship
with Helen Keller
came from childhood.

51:59.366 --> 52:04.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
She was held up as this
role model that she
was deaf and blind, but
she was always cheerful

52:05.833 --> 52:09.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and she did well in school and
you never heard her complain.

52:09.066 --> 52:10.666 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I took this very personally.

52:10.666 --> 52:15.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I took this as a
reproach towards me.

52:15.366 --> 52:20.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I hated Helen Keller and I
loved Helen Keller jokes and
I, you know, told them with

52:23.300 --> 52:26.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
relish in the schoolyard.

52:26.466 --> 52:31.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I started to wonder if I
had been unfair to Helen
Keller when I was a child.

52:33.433 --> 52:37.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I ended up writing a book
about her, which is a series
of letters by me, to her, and

52:39.433 --> 52:42.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
she doesn't write back
because she's dead.

52:42.000 --> 52:46.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's basically me asking
questions about different
moments in her life
and calling her out and

52:51.233 --> 52:53.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
asking her to explain herself.

52:53.633 --> 52:57.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so, it was a way for me to
enter her life imaginatively.

52:57.633 --> 53:02.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I tell my students all the
time that they should tell
their friends not to text while

53:04.600 --> 53:09.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
walking because I am always
bumping into people who
are texting while walking.

53:11.533 --> 53:16.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then they make themselves
a hazard to blind people,
because I am counting on all

53:18.100 --> 53:21.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the other pedestrians to pay
attention, to see me coming
and to get out of my way.

53:24.433 --> 53:29.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I think there is still
discrimination in
all sorts of arenas.

53:29.000 --> 53:34.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's problems with access
to Web sites and electronic
media and so on and so forth,

53:36.833 --> 53:38.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
captioning, audio description.

53:38.833 --> 53:42.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The technology exists, people
know how to do this, but
it's not as if everything is

53:42.900 --> 53:45.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
made accessible.

53:45.033 --> 53:50.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The problem is that
people's understanding of
blindness is very limited.

53:52.466 --> 53:56.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's the sort of
joke scenario of a blind
person coming to an
intersection and somebody

53:58.033 --> 54:01.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
grabbing their arm and leading
them across the street when
in fact they wanted to go

54:01.433 --> 54:03.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in a different direction.

54:03.466 --> 54:07.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's never happened to me
and I think part of it is jus
that I tend to look like I know

54:10.400 --> 54:12.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
where I'm going.

54:12.333 --> 54:15.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: I
would agree with that.

54:15.400 --> 54:17.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

54:17.433 --> 54:21.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KLEEGE: My name is Georgina
Kleege and this is my brief but
spectacular take on blindness.

54:22.166 --> 54:23.833 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(END VIDEOTAPE)

54:23.833 --> 54:26.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
WOODRUFF: And we
thank you, Georgina.

